06792nam a22007095i 9780822395065DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20152012ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223950657 a10.1515/97808223950652doi  a(DE-B1597)552849  a(OCoLC)908507295  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aHIS0330002bisacsh04a333.3/18122300aChallenging Social Inequality :bThe Landless Rural Workers Movement and Agrarian Reform in Brazil /cMiguel Carter. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2015] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (544 p.) :b45 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Figures, Maps, and Tables -- tList of Abbreviations -- tAn Overview -- t1. Social Inequality, Agrarian Reform, and Democracy in Brazil -- tPart I. The Agrarian Question and Rural Social Movements in Brazil -- t2. The Agrarian Question and Agribusiness in Brazil -- t3. Rural Social Movements, Struggles for Rights, and Land Reform in Contemporary Brazilian History -- t4. Churches, the Pastoral Land Commission, and the Mobilization for Agrarian Reform -- tPart II. MST History and Struggle for Land -- t5. The Formation and Territorialization of the MST in Brazil -- t6. Origins and Consolidation of the MST in Rio Grande do Sul -- t7. Under the Black Tarp -- t8. From Posseiro to Sem Terra -- tPart III. MST's Agricultural Settlements -- t9. The Struggle on the Land -- t10. Rural Settlements and the MST in São Paulo -- t11. Community Building in an MST Settlement in Northeast Brazil -- t12. MST Settlements in Pernambuco -- tPart IV. The MST, Politics, and Society in Brazil -- t13. Working with Governments -- t14. The MST and the Rule of Law in Brazil -- t15. Beyond the MST -- tConclusion. Challenging Social Inequality -- tEpilogue. Broken Promise -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Challenging Social Inequality, an international and interdisciplinary group of scholars and development workers explores the causes, consequences, and contemporary reactions to Brazil's sharply unequal agrarian structure. They focus on the Landless Rural Workers Movement (MST)-Latin America's largest and most prominent social movement-and its ongoing efforts to confront historic patterns of inequality in the Brazilian countryside. Several essays provide essential historical background for understanding the MST. They examine Brazil's agrarian structure, state policies, and the formation of rural civil-society organizations. Other essays build on a frequently made distinction between the struggle for land and the struggle on the land. The first refers to the mobilization undertaken by landless peasants to demand government land redistribution. The struggle on the land takes place after the establishment of an official agricultural settlement. The main efforts during this phase are geared toward developing productive and meaningful rural communities. The last essays in the collection are wide-ranging analyses of the MST, which delve into the movement's relations with recent governments and its impact on other Brazilian social movements. In the conclusion, Miguel Carter appraises the future of agrarian reform in Brazil.Contributors. José Batista Gonçalves Afonso, Sonia Maria P..P. Bergamasco, Sue Branford, Elena Calvo-González, Miguel Carter, Horacio Martins de Carvalho, Guilherme Costa Delgado, Bernardo Mançano Fernandes, Leonilde Sérvolo de Medeiros, George Mészáros, Luiz Antonio Norder, Gabriel Ondetti, Ivo Poletto, Marcelo Carvalho Rosa, Lygia Maria Sigaud, Emmanuel Wambergue, Wendy Wolford  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South Am